1,"A mid-size manufacturing company (200 employees) has seen a 15% decline in quarterly revenue. The CEO proposes cutting the R&D budget by 40% to preserve short-term profitability. The R&D team is currently developing two products expected to launch within 18 months.","CEO, CFO, R&D Director, Production Manager, Board of Directors","Should the company cut R&D spending by 40%? What factors should inform this decision?","The decision involves trade-offs between short-term financial stability and long-term competitiveness. Factors to consider: (1) projected revenue from the two in-development products vs. the 40% savings, (2) risk of losing R&D talent who may leave if projects are cancelled, (3) competitive positioning if rivals continue investing in innovation, (4) alternative cost-reduction measures (operational efficiency, non-essential spending), (5) board and investor expectations for both quarterly results and growth pipeline. A partial cut or phased reduction could balance both objectives.",moderate,resource_allocation
2,"A hospital's emergency department averages 4-hour wait times, double the national benchmark. Management is considering two options: (A) hire 8 additional nurses at $640K/year total cost, or (B) implement an AI triage system at $200K upfront plus $50K/year maintenance. Staff nurses have expressed concern about the AI system's reliability.","Hospital Administrator, Chief Nursing Officer, ER Physicians, Nursing Staff, Patients, IT Department","Which option should the hospital pursue, and why?","Both options have merit but address different aspects of the problem. Option A directly increases capacity and is proven, but has higher ongoing cost. Option B is cheaper long-term but introduces clinical risk if the AI triage is unreliable, and staff resistance could undermine adoption. Key considerations: (1) root cause analysis — are wait times due to staffing shortages or inefficient triage, (2) patient safety implications of AI-assisted triage, (3) regulatory requirements for clinical decision support tools, (4) staff buy-in and change management needs, (5) possibility of a phased approach combining both. The decision should not be framed as either/or without understanding the underlying bottleneck.",complex,operations
